        Chart Review 22/03/24

        guys i'm not happy.

        Welcome to the annual musical hoodwinking that goes on every 7 years, where I type these words while jiving to artists you've never heard of like 'Idlewild' and 'Plan B' (except people actually know who he is), and make snide comments about folk that are all better than me in the musical department. This week gives me the opportunity to act more cynical than usual, as a whopping TWO new entries can be found amongst the best-sellers, and they're both worthy enough for me to waste one or two paragraphs over them. Even though they matter as much to the Top 40 nowadays as Vera Lynn and Winifred Atwell.

        There are two re-entrants this week, so I might as well get them out the way. First up, I regret to inform you that the awful Birds In The Sky by NewEra has returned after a couple weeks out at 34, and it still sounds as bad as modern EDM gets nowadays. Apparently there's a new remix of this tune out now that features fellow (hopefully) 1-hit wonder Mazza_l20, he of surprise Top 20 hit Murdaside (which I forgot to talk about in recent times), and who's been barred off Radio 1 on the basis that he's been incarcerated as of recent times. Look, NewEra, whatever goodwill you're trying to do for the music industry keeps going horribly wrong. You don't wanna end up busking for money like 90% of your chart rivals will be by 2040, do you? Anyways, Never Lose Me by Flo Milli jumps back in as well at 23, helped by A) her new album arriving online, and B) a new version with SZA and Cardi B pretending to care about someone who sounds eerily like the two of 'em. Who knew Attack Of The Clones was so influential, eh?

        Anyways, there's a new No.1 this week.

        And not a very good one.

        You see, I have this thing written on my brain's checklist, stating that if you're gonna top the chart, you'll need to actually have proof that you can make quality music. Of course, it never stopped ultimate 1-hit wonders 3 of a Kind in 2004, but even the worst of the worst have made 1 or 2 songs that get my interest. This is the point where 21 year-old Washington native Benson Boone needs to up his game. 'Cause he's top of the charts now.

        As we all know by now, I hate Beautiful Things, mainly because it stupidly chooses to imitate Sam Ryder's ouevre (is that how you spell it?) and yell over the chorus like he just stood on LEGO. Even for a rock-loving, Marilyn Manson-serenading guy like me, this is just too much to handle. The likes of Lewis Capaldi specialise in this technique, and it's a trick that poor old Benson has been quick to cash in on. Having said that, I never really thought he'd be No.1 material. Until now of course, as he deposes Beyoncé after 4 weeks of playing second/third fiddle. As you can probably tell, I am distraught, and am planning a nuclear strike on his current location as we speak, but if he can get to No.1 after several weeks, then it's clear to see that something about it works. Unfortunately, I just can't tell what it is. And I'm far from the only one to cry wolf about this. Still though, well done Benson I guess, and good luck trying to follow it up. I mean, you can't do any worse than Kenya Grace, can you? The only thing I can add to this is, why is he posing with his award like there's a shotgun pointed at him offscreen? Mate, it's just BBC One's The One Show, it's not like you're on Squid Game or anything.

        Beyoncé thus falls to 3, usurped in the battle for the runner-up spot by Ariana Grande, and the album track that's gonna end up far bigger than she thought. we can't be friends (wait for your love) should've been No.1 instead, but then again, it's a pretty low bar to clear. And given Teddy Swims is back in the Top 5, I would rather that bar be raised a lot higher. Props to Ariana, though, for holding on to her No.1 album spot, becoming the first LP since Taylor Swift's 1989 (TV) to spend consecutive weeks at the summit. Small mercies for Kacey Musgraves then, who sees her new album go in at 3, while Justin Timberlake goes in at 5 with his new one. Selfish, though, hasn't returned to the Top 40. So yeah, no, he's done out. As Smash Hits famously quoted, it's safe to say he's down the dumper.

        It's also a sad moment to say that the limp and fragile Scared To Start by Michael Marcagi has crawled into the Top 10 now, and that sound you can hear while it plays is the groan of a 17 year-old crying into his pillows, at the sight of how down bad the music scene is nowadays. I feel like a middle-aged dad at this point, which doesn't bode well for the future. I mean, could you imagine me by the time we get to the 2030s? You can't, can you. I'll have given up by then. 🏳️

        There are two new hits today, as I've already said, and both couldn't be further apart in relations to each other if they joined NASA and piloted to Mars. In at 13 in the latest in a long, long (oh my gosh, it's so long) line of solo BTS projects that I routinely diss every time they make a chart impact. In this case, it's the second appearance of forgotten man 'V' to the UK Top 40, after September's 1-week wonder Slow Dancing. And what a surprise, it's boring and homogenous. Clearly the most interesting thing about it is the title, FRI(END)S, given the song has already fallen out of my memory banks as I'm typing this. It does debut 11 places higher than his last effort, so I guess that's a positive. Even though it just isn't. Like, at all.

        As for No.18, um... I had no clue this was gonna do so well. For those who don't know, Mark Knopfler was the lead singer of everyone's favourite 80s dad band Dire Straits, who had huge success with that Brothers In Arms album, along with smash hits like Money For Nothing and Sultans Of Swing. In 1983, Mark felt like sticking a song called Going Home out, as part of the soundtrack for Local Hero. It stiffed, peaking at 56, even though it plays every single time Newcastle United kick-off nowadays. For some reason, Mark felt it was a good idea to get as many guitar legends as possible to record a new version, which is alright, I guess. What nobody expected was the fact it was No.1 in the midweeks, before casually sinking away in a fashion that would impress Liam Gallagher, but does at least enter at 18. Of course, you'll need to seek this one out for yourself, given it's nearly 10 minutes long, and you're just hearing a bunch of guitar noodling that sounds not unlike that most dreaded of music genres, PROG ROCK. A list of everyone I know will be in my P.S. section at the end. Either way, it's his first Top 40 appearance since Boom, Like That hit 34 in 2004 and I for one will be amazed if it stays in the Top 100 next week. Might as well hope for the best, in this current climate.

        Narrowly missing out are Jungle at 41 which, I mean, it's fine, it's already been in the Top 40, I don't really care if it misses out. Rudimental go up to 43 so at least you know who to keep track of next time out, Dimitri Vegas's Dido refurbishment has climbed to 50, Jax Jones has rocketed up to my dismay, Meghan Trainor's back at 60, Cardi B's new one flops at 85, ZAYN continues to ruin his chart ambitions at 89, and some guy called Mark Ambor debuts at 94. Just a shame that he sounds like generic countryside fluff then.

        Going into the charts next week include Bryson Tiller's new one, Benson Boone's new one, Kenya Grace's new one (sensing a pattern yet?), Hozier's new one, and O-Rod's new one, while the album charts will involve afrobeats princess Tyla, Mancunian elder statesmen Elbow, and Future and Metro Boomin feeling like it's a good idea to do some collab album or whatever. And I'll be here to inform you of all the goings-on. Although, it's not like you'll care about any of them. BYE!!!



        (P.S. The Mark Knopfler charity song includes Joan Armatrading, Jeff Beck, Eric Clapton, Paul Carrack, Sheryl Crow, Roger Daltrey, Sam Fender, David Gilmour, Joan Jett, Hank Marvin, Brian May, Tom Morello, Nile Rodgers, Mike Rutherford, Slash, Bruce Springsteen, Ringo Starr, Sting, Andy Taylor, Pete Townshend, Keith Urban, Ronnie Wood, and Zucchero. And a bunch of other people I haven't heard of.)

        Congratulations to Benson Boone on his first #1 hit, but I really hope this doesn’t stay there for long or I could see it grating on me even more.
